history.content: The circuits in 105 are significantly more in depth than compared to 16B.  In all honesty, the circuits in 16B give little to no hint whatsoever as to what analog/RF circuit design is about.  See @11402 for more on 105.  While an embedded systems designer is unlikely to use all the integrated circuits knowledge 105 teaches, it is still important to know the basic analog constraints real world circuits have, since while much of embedded systems are digitally controlled, the real world is still analog!  So I'd say 105 is necessary, but 140 (where we go in depth in integrated circuits) is not for the embedded systems engineer.  Cheers!
